                            </list>
                        </item>
                        <item><ref type="apparatus" subtype="manuscript" target="msiii_apparatus.php"><hi rend="bold"><title type="manuscript" corresp="#MSIII">MS III</title></hi></ref>
                            <list>
                        <item><ref type="witness" target="the_ship_msiii.php"><title type="poem" corresp="#JRTHESHIP182829">&#x201C;The Ship&#x201D; [<date notBefore="1828" notAfter="1829">1828&#x2013;29</date>]</title></ref></item>
                    </list>  
                </item>
                </list>
                </div>
                
                <div type="section" xml:id="TITLE">
                    <head type="section"><title type="poem" corresp="#JRTHESHIP182829">&#x201C;The Ship&#x201D; [<date notBefore="1828" notAfter="1829">1828&#x2013;29</date>]</title></head>
                    <p><persName corresp="#JR">Ruskin</persName> wrote the title as &#x201C;The ship&#x201D; in <title type="manuscript" corresp="#MSII">MS II</title>, and as &#x201C;THE SHIP&#x201D; in <title type="manuscript" corresp="#MSIII">MS III</title>.</p>
                    <p>See <ref type="note" subtype="bibliographical" target="title_citation_note.php">System of Title Citation for Works</ref>.</p>
                </div>
                
                <div type="section" xml:id="GENRE">
                    <head type="section">Genre</head>
                    <p>Poem.</p>
                </div>
                
                <div type="section" xml:id="MAJORMS">
                    <head type="section">Manuscripts</head>
                    <p><title type="manuscript" corresp="#MSII">MS II</title>, <title type="manuscript" corresp="#MSIII">MS III</title>.</p>
                    <p>Facsimiles by permission of <title type="archive" corresp="#BEINECKERUSKINCOLLECTION">John Ruskin Collection</title>, General Collection, <orgName corresp="#BEINECKE">Beinecke Rare Book and Manuscript Library</orgName>, <orgName corresp="#YALE">Yale University</orgName>. Transcriptions of texts and commentary &#x00A9; <persName corresp="#DCH">David C. Hanson</persName>.</p>
                </div>
                
                <div type="section" xml:id="DATE">
                    <head type="section">Date</head>
                    <p>A draft appears as the first item in the handmade booklet, <title type="manuscript" corresp="#MSII">MS II</title>, preceding draft of 
                        <ref type="apparatus" target="harry_and_lucy_vol3_apparatus.php"><title type="lesson" corresp="#JRHARRYANDLUCYVOL3">&#x201C;Harry and Lucy . . . Vol III&#x201D;</title></ref>, 
                        which <persName corresp="#JR">Ruskin</persName> must have been written toward the end of <date when="1828">1828</date>. Substitutions in this draft are accounted for in a fair copy in <title type="manuscript" corresp="#MSIII">MS III</title>, 
                        so the latter witness definitely dates from a later time, 
                        likely from around <date when="1828-03-09">9 March 1829</date>, since it is included in a group of poems given that date in manuscript 
                        (see <ref type="apparatus" target="of_rocks_first_and_of_caverns_now_i_sing_apparatus.xml"><title type="poem" corresp="#JROFROCKSFIRST">&#x201C;Of rocks first and of caverns now I sing&#x201D;</title></ref>).</p>
                </div>
                
                <div type="section" xml:id="COMPPUB">
                    <head type="section">Composition and Publication</head>
                    <p>Previously unpublished in its entirety. Published in part in 
                        <ref type="bibliography" target="bibliography.php#POEMS4D1891"><title type="book" corresp="#POEMS4D1891"><hi rend="italic">Poems</hi> (4<hi rend="superscript">o</hi>, 1891)</title></ref>,1:269; and 
                        <ref type="bibliography" target="bibliography.php#POEMS8D1891"><title type="book" corresp="#POEMS8D1891"><hi rend="italic">Poems</hi> (8<hi rend="superscript">o</hi>, 1891)</title></ref>, 1:270; and
                        <ref type="bibliography" target="bibliography.php#JRWORKSLE"><persName corresp="#JR">Ruskin</persName>, <title type="book" corresp="JRWORKSLE"><hi rend="italic">Works</hi></title></ref>, 2:264n.</p>
                </div>
                
                <div type="section" xml:id="DISCUSSION">
                    <head type="section">Discussion</head>
                    <p>See the discussion of an earlier poem, <ref type="apparatus" target="look_at_that_ship_apparatus.php#DISCUSSION"><title type="poem" corresp="#JRTHESHIP1827">&#x201C;The Ship&#x201D; <hi rend="italic">and</hi> &#x201C;Look at That Ship&#x201D; [<date when="1827">1827</date>]</title></ref>.
                        The earlier poem shares a similar, though not identical, set of first six lines with the present poem; thereafter, however, the new poem swerves in a quite different direction, 
                        so much so that the new poem cannot be considered a version of the earlier one.</p>
                    <p><persName corresp="#JR">Ruskin</persName> was inspired to this revision by a sight encountered during the 
                        <ref type="note" subtype="contextual" target="tour_of_1828_note.php">Tour of <date when="1828">1828</date></ref>. As he in the 
                        <ref type="apparatus" subtype="work" target="travel_itinerary_and_tour_notes_1828_apparatus.php"><title type="manual_guide" corresp="#JRTRAVELITINERARY1828">Travel Itinerary and Tour Notes [<date when="1828">1828</date>]</title></ref>, 
                        the family, when crossing from <placeName corresp="#PORTSMOUTH">Portsmouth</placeName> to the <placeName corresp="#ISLEOFWIGHT">Isle of Wight</placeName>, 
                        could see the &#x201C;place where <name type="vessel" corresp="#ROYALGEORGE">royal george</name> sunk,&#x201D; a catastrophe incorporated into the revised poem. 
                        The site of this famous disaster, which occurred in <date when="1782">1782</date>, is pointed out in travel guides published throughout the nineteenth century, 
                        long after the ship&#x02BC;s wreckage presented a visible reminder of the catastrophe. See the glosses to the poem for details.</p>
                    <p>At line 21 of the <title type="manuscript" corresp="#MSIII">MS III</title> version of <title type="poem" corresp="#JRTHESHIP182829">&#x201C;The Ship&#x201D; [<date notBefore="1828" notAfter="1829">1828&#x2010;29</date>]</title>, 
                        a line that starts a new page (p. 40) in that manuscript, <persName corresp="#JR">Ruskin</persName> abruptly reduces the size of his lettering and squeezes the lines closer together, 
                        possibly suggesting that he was running out of room for this fair copy. Nothing in the <title type="manuscript" corresp="#MSII">MS II</title> draft indicates that <persName corresp="#JR">Ruskin</persName> suddenly decided to lengthen the poem. 
                        In <title type="manuscript" corresp="#MSIII">MS III</title>, perhaps he had already begun to fair&#x2010;copy  
                        <ref type="apparatus" target="sonnet_to_the_sun_apparatus.php"><title type="poem" corresp="#SONNETTOTHESUN">&#x201C;Sonnet to the Sun&#x201D;</title></ref>, which follows 
                        <title type="poem" corresp="#JRTHESHIP182829">&#x201C;The Ship&#x201D; [<date notBefore="1828" notAfter="1829">1828&#x2010;29</date>]</title> 
                        in the anthology, but discovered that he had left insufficient space.</p>
                </div>
            </div>
